                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18210214-62-off397 t18210214-62-crimeloc400"></join>. The prisoner was my <rs id="t18210214-62-deflabel401" type="occupation">carman</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18210214-62-defend739 t18210214-62-deflabel401"></join>; I missed some hay, and mentioned it to him. On the the 24th of January, I received information; I ran home and saw the prisoner at the wharf. I told him it was not the first time he had robbed me, and I should take him. He begged forgiveness, as it was his first offence, and said he would work it out. On going to the watch-house, he bolted from us. The next morning I found him in custody.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18210214-62-person743">
                  JOHN 
                  PARSONS
               <interp inst="t18210214-62-person743" type="surname" value="PARSONS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18210214-62-person743" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18210214-62-person743" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a patrol. On the 24th of January, about seven o'clock, I was on my beat in East Smithfield, I saw the prisoner with a truss of hay. I was informed he had offered it for sale. He told me he was going to Nightingale-lane; I took it from him, he went away, and was afterwards brought to the watch-house.</p>
